---
import ProjectLayout from "../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro";
import PhotoGallery from "../../components/PhotoGallery.jsx";
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="OERC Research — Maritime Autonomy"
  subtitle="Ocean Engineering Research Center · Supervised by Dr. Wei Qiu · Jan – May 2026"
  logo="/logos/mun-engineering.png"
  logoAlt="MUN Engineering"
  logoClass="bg-white/10 p-1"
  context="Work"
  tags={["C++17", "Qt 6", "OpenGL", "GLSL", "NURBS", "IGES", "Arduino", "Raspberry Pi", "LiDAR", "PID Control", "KiCad", "OpenCV", "CMake"]}
>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="font-display text-lg font-600 text-white/80 mb-4">Overview</h2>
    <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
      Three projects under Dr. Wei Qiu at Memorial's Ocean Engineering Research Center.
      I built a C++/OpenGL desktop app for hull geometry visualization and hydrodynamic analysis,
      wrote a research report on autonomous vessel communications for IMO/Transport Canada,
      and designed and built AEGIS, a scale-model autonomous SAR vessel, from scratch.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="font-display text-lg font-600 text-white/80 mb-6">Projects</h2>
    <div class="space-y-8">

      <!-- AEGIS -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-1">AEGIS — Autonomous SAR Vessel</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">Arduino · Raspberry Pi Zero 2 W · LiDAR · MLX90640 · OpenCV · KiCad</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-5">
          <p>
            AEGIS (Autonomous Environmental Guardian for Intelligent Search-and-Rescue) is a
            scale-model vessel targeting <span class="text-white/70">IMO Level 2/3 autonomy</span>.
            The problem it addresses is straightforward: Canada has the longest coastline in the world,
            Arctic conditions make crewed SAR patrols dangerous and expensive, and existing fleets
            can't cover it all. AEGIS is meant to fill that gap as a forward-deployed thermal search
            drone that gets to the scene ahead of Coast Guard crews, scanning for people in the water
            and relaying conditions back to shore. The autonomy and comms architecture came out of
            my <a href="#mass-report" class="text-white/70 underline underline-offset-2 decoration-white/20 hover:decoration-white/40">MASS connectivity research</a>,
            which I did first specifically to figure out how a vessel like this should handle
            sensor fusion, decision-making, and connectivity failover when satellite links drop.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Platform & propulsion</h4>
          <p>
            An <span class="text-white/70">Arduino Uno</span> drives the propulsion system through
            an <span class="text-white/70">L298N dual H-bridge</span> controlling a brushed DC
            thruster motor and a rudder servo. Two <span class="text-white/70">VL53L0X LiDAR
            sensors</span> (forward and starboard) feed distance readings into a
            <span class="text-white/70">PID control loop</span> running at ~50 Hz for wall tracking
            and obstacle avoidance. Tuning the PID gains for the tank environment took most of
            the testing time since the hull's drag characteristics change a lot between dry-run
            bench tests and actual water.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Dual-processor architecture</h4>
          <p>
            The system splits across two processors over <span class="text-white/70">UART serial
            </span> at 115200 baud. The Uno handles all real-time motor
            <span class="text-white/70">PID</span> and rudder control, because it needs
            deterministic loop timing and the Pi can't guarantee that. The
            <span class="text-white/70">Raspberry Pi Zero 2 W</span> runs the compute-heavy
            side: thermal imaging pipeline, camera-based obstacle detection through
            <span class="text-white/70">OpenCV</span>,
            <span class="text-white/70">GPS/IMU</span> logging at 10 Hz, WiFi telemetry to the
            ground station, and 3D thermal map compositing. Commands flow Pi-to-Uno as simple
            ASCII packets (heading setpoints, speed targets), and the Uno sends back sensor
            telemetry and status flags.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Thermal scanning & detection</h4>
          <p>
            The SAR payload is an <span class="text-white/70">MLX90640 32×24 thermal array</span>
            on a servo mount. It sweeps four positions using the sensor's 110° FOV to get full
            360° azimuth coverage. Each frame is tagged with
            <span class="text-white/70">GPS coordinates</span> and <span class="text-white/70">IMU
            orientation</span>, logged to SD card and optionally streamed to the ground station
            over WiFi. The frames composite into a
            <span class="text-white/70">3D thermal point cloud</span> of the vessel's
            surroundings. Human body heat (~30°C+) stands out clearly against open water
            at ~2-4°C, so the detection threshold is generous. When the system picks up a
            warm cluster, it locks the heading, triggers indicator LEDs and a piezo buzzer, and
            logs the GPS fix.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Proposed: camera-based pathfinding</h4>
          <p class="text-white/40">
            Next sensor to add (if time and budget allow) is a <span class="text-white/50">Pi
            Camera Module</span> on the CSI port for forward-looking obstacle detection via
            <span class="text-white/50">OpenCV</span>. The LiDAR gives range-based avoidance but
            can't tell you what the obstacle is. A camera feed with basic classification would
            let the vessel distinguish debris from a kayak from a wave crest.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">In progress: custom carrier PCB</h4>
          <p class="text-white/40">
            I'm designing a <span class="text-white/50">KiCad carrier PCB</span> that mounts
            under the Pi Zero 2 W as a HAT-style board. It consolidates
            <span class="text-white/50">power regulation</span> (5 V and 3.3 V rails from a
            single LiPo input),
            <span class="text-white/50">I2C</span> sensor headers for the MLX90640, GPS, and IMU,
            servo PWM output, UART crossover to the Uno, CSI passthrough for the camera, and
            status LEDs. Basically replacing the rats-nest of breadboard jumper wires with
            a single board.
          </p>
        </div>
        <PhotoGallery
          client:only="react"
          images={[
            { src: "/projects/oerc/boat-thumb.png", alt: "Autonomous model vessel — side view", caption: "Side profile of the completed autonomous model vessel on its display stand" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/topfrontviewboat.jpg", alt: "Top-down view of vessel internals", caption: "Top-down view showing sensor mounts, wiring, and electronics layout" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/comp-1.jpg", alt: "AEGIS project poster and vessel display", caption: "AEGIS: Autonomous Environmental Guardian for Intelligent Search and Rescue — competition poster with vessel" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/comp-2.jpg", alt: "Team photo at competition", caption: "Team presenting the autonomous vessel at the engineering competition" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/boatwork1.jpg", alt: "Workshop — prototyping and testing", caption: "Workshop session — prototyping and testing components" },
            { video: "/projects/oerc/boat-vid-1.mp4", alt: "Vessel testing video 1", caption: "Testing the autonomous vessel" },
            { video: "/projects/oerc/boat-vid-2.mp4", alt: "Vessel testing video 2", caption: "Tank testing — wall tracking and obstacle avoidance" },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <!-- MAPS Desktop Client -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-1">MAPS Desktop Client — NURBS Surface Viewer & Seakeeping Suite</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">C++17 · Qt 6 · OpenGL ES 2.0 · GLSL · CMake · MSVC 2022</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            <span class="text-white/70">MAPS</span> is a frequency-domain potential flow solver
            for wave-body interaction analysis, developed at the OERC. It had no GUI. You'd hand-edit
            plaintext <span class="text-white/70">.in</span> config files, run the binary from a
            terminal, then parse output files separately. I built a desktop app in
            <span class="text-white/70">C++17</span> and <span class="text-white/70">Qt 6</span>
            that wraps the full pipeline: geometry import and inspection, solver configuration and
            execution, and post-processing with interactive charts, all in one window.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Geometry & visualization</h4>
          <p>
            The viewer reads <span class="text-white/70">IGES files</span> (Entity 128 NURBS
            surfaces) and tessellates them on the GPU through custom
            <span class="text-white/70">GLSL shaders</span> with per-fragment Phong lighting.
            Each hull body sits in a shared world-space coordinate system with its own position,
            heading, and color palette, so you can load multi-body configs (catamarans, trimaran
            floats, barges alongside a vessel) and see them together. Surface normals are editable
            per-patch with full undo and IGES rewrite, since MAPS is sensitive to normal
            orientation and a single flipped patch will blow up the solution. The app also overlays
            MAPS <span class="text-white/70">.geom</span> output, plotting the computed
            <span class="text-white/70">Gaussian quadrature points</span> and evaluated surface
            normals directly on the mesh so you can verify discretization quality before running
            a full solve.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Analysis workflow</h4>
          <p>
            All MAPS input parameters are exposed through form dialogs: principal dimensions,
            mass and inertia matrices, wave heading and frequency ranges, per-patch Gauss point
            counts, and 25+ solver control flags. The app assembles the complete
            <span class="text-white/70">.in project file</span> and launches the solver
            as a child process with stdout piped to a console widget in real time. It handles
            zero-speed and forward-speed formulations,
            <span class="text-white/70">irregular frequency removal</span>, mean drift forces
            (near-field and far-field), catamaran/trimaran rigid-body coupling, and random sea
            spectral statistics (Pierson-Moskowitz, JONSWAP).
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Results viewer</h4>
          <p>
            Interactive charts for <span class="text-white/70">motion RAOs</span>,
            <span class="text-white/70">added mass</span>, damping coefficients, and wave
            exciting forces across all six degrees of freedom. Drag-to-zoom, hover tooltips
            with exact values, scientific notation on axes. You can load multiple result files
            and compare them side by side with stable per-dataset color assignment across 10
            high-contrast colors. Added mass is displayed in tonnes with a full
            <span class="text-white/70">6×6 coupling matrix</span> view or diagonal-only,
            depending on whether you care about cross-coupling terms.
          </p>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-dashed border-white/10 p-8 text-center text-sm text-white/25 font-mono">
            Screenshots coming soon
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MASS report -->
      <div id="mass-report" class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-2">MASS connectivity research</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">Technical writing · IMO standards · Transport Canada</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed">
          A research report I wrote on communication requirements for Maritime Autonomous Surface
          Ships (MASS). I mapped out what connectivity each IMO autonomy degree actually needs
          at each operational phase (departure, transit, arrival, emergency), then cross-referenced
          with Transport Canada's regulatory framework to find the gaps. This is the work that
          shaped AEGIS's comms architecture, specifically around what the vessel should stream
          live vs. log locally, and how it should degrade gracefully when satellite links fail.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>